Based on the provided spec, here is a structured execution plan for the Fabricator Management Platform 

```text
FABRICATOR MANAGEMENT PLATFORM
UI-ONLY SaaS APPLICATION — EXECUTION PLAN

1) FULL CONTEXT / PRODUCT DEFINITION

1.1 Product Objective
- Build a professional, enterprise-grade, UI-only SaaS web application for fabricators, traders, and distributors.
- The platform should feel like a real operational business tool, not a demo dashboard or a simple CRUD app.
- It must simulate monetization, operations, intelligence, finance, and ecosystem management using mock data only.
- No backend, no real APIs, no third-party integrations.
- The UI should be production-like, scalable, and ready to be connected to backend services later.

1.2 Primary Business Purpose
- Manage fabrication projects from intake to processing.
- Track and simulate inventory movement and consumption.
- Apply pricing rules dynamically based on region/customer/material.
- Show SaaS monetization through wallet, SFT billing, and credit deduction.
- Track invoices, payments, reports, and operational finance.
- Visualize supply chain relationships.
- Support OCR-based document intake and AI-assisted extraction.
- Provide admin controls for pricing, usage, and system health.
- Support offline mode and multilingual UI.

1.3 Product Positioning
- This is a serious B2B SaaS platform for operational teams.
- It should look like a mix of ERP, fintech dashboard, and industrial operations software.
- Visual tone: neutral, dense, clean, structured, high-trust, business-first.
- The experience must be clear enough for real-world users such as owners, operators, finance teams, and warehouse managers.

1.4 Core Navigation Structure
- Dashboard
- Projects
- Inventory
- Pricing Engine
- Billing & Wallet
- Payments
- Supply Chain
- OCR Uploads
- Reports (CA / GST)
- Batch Processing
- Admin Panel
- Settings

1.5 Global UI Expectations
- Left sidebar navigation
- Top header with:
  - search
  - organization switcher
  - notifications
  - profile
  - wallet balance
- Main content area with:
  - cards
  - tables
  - charts
  - drawers
  - modals
- Strong spacing and grid discipline
- Dense but readable enterprise tables
- Semantic colors for statuses
- Reusable UI components
- Mock JSON data
- Clear state indicators everywhere
- Sorting, filtering, and search in tables
- Modals and side drawers for create/edit/process actions
- Stepper/workflow indicators where relevant

1.6 Key Domain Data Objects
- Projects: id, name, client, sft, status, cost, created_at
- Inventory: id, item_name, category, quantity, unit, location, status
- Wallet: balance, credits_used, credits_added, transactions
- Invoices: id, client, amount, status, due_date, paid_date
- Pricing rules: id, region, customer_type, material, price_per_sft
- OCR files: id, file_url, extracted_data, validation_status

1.7 Business Capabilities to Simulate
- SFT billing and deduction
- Inventory consumption based on BOM processing
- Pricing calculation based on rule engine
- Invoice generation and payment tracking
- Revenue and credit purchase simulation
- Batch optimization preview
- OCR extraction and manual validation
- Offline action queue and sync behavior
- Language switching with visible UI text variation

2) POINT-WISE EXECUTION PLAN

PHASE 1 — PRODUCT FOUNDATION

2.1 Set up the application shell
- Build the overall layout first:
  - sidebar
  - topbar
  - content container
  - responsive behavior
- Create the base navigation system.
- Establish the app frame that all modules will share.
- Add workspace patterns for:
  - full page views
  - nested detail screens
  - drawers
  - dialogs
  - empty states

2.2 Define the visual system
- Establish typography scale.
- Define spacing rules and layout rhythm.
- Create a restrained color system:
  - primary
  - secondary
  - success
  - warning
  - danger
  - info
  - neutral
- Define status badge styles:
  - active
  - completed
  - pending
  - error
  - overdue
  - low stock
- Standardize surface styles:
  - cards
  - tables
  - panels
  - modals
  - side drawers

2.3 Create reusable UI components
- Button
- Input
- Select
- Badge
- Tag / Chip
- Table
- Pagination
- Tabs
- Drawer
- Modal
- Toast
- Timeline
- Stepper
- Metric card
- Chart wrapper
- Search bar
- Filter bar
- Empty state
- Loading skeleton
- File upload zone
- Status indicator
- Currency display
- Progress bar
- Notification item

2.4 Establish mock data architecture
- Create realistic JSON datasets for:
  - projects
  - inventory
  - pricing rules
  - invoices
  - payments
  - wallet transactions
  - OCR files
  - supply chain entities
  - activity logs
  - admin metrics
- Ensure mock data includes:
  - normal cases
  - edge cases
  - low stock
  - overdue payments
  - completed projects
  - pending OCR validations
  - offline pending actions

PHASE 2 — GLOBAL APPLICATION EXPERIENCE

2.5 Implement the top header
- Search input with global search behavior.
- Organization switcher with multi-org feel.
- Notification bell with unread state.
- Wallet balance display.
- Profile menu.
- Language selector.
- Offline status badge.

2.6 Implement the sidebar navigation
- Add all modules in the correct hierarchy.
- Use clear labels and icons.
- Include active route highlighting.
- Support collapsed and expanded states.
- Keep the sidebar enterprise-like, not decorative.

2.7 Add global system states
- Offline banner
- Sync pending banner
- Error toast pattern
- Warning banner
- Success confirmation
- Permission / admin state styling
- Empty data states
- Search no-result states

2.8 Establish table behavior standards
- Sorting
- Filtering
- Global search
- Column visibility
- Row actions
- Pagination or infinite scroll where needed
- Multi-select actions for batch operations

PHASE 3 — DASHBOARD MODULE

2.9 Build the dashboard overview
- Show a high-level operational summary.
- Structure it like a serious SaaS control center.

2.10 Add KPI cards
- Total SFT processed
- Wallet balance
- Revenue generated
- Pending invoices
- Low stock alerts
- Active projects

2.11 Add usage meter
- Show SFT consumption versus available credits.
- Present progress clearly with thresholds.
- Add warning states for nearing limit.

2.12 Add revenue graph
- Show simulated SaaS earnings over time.
- Include daily / weekly / monthly switch.
- Add trend comparison.

2.13 Add inventory alerts panel
- Display low stock items.
- Show item name, category, and severity.
- Allow quick access to inventory detail.

2.14 Add recent activity timeline
- Show recent actions like:
  - project created
  - inventory adjusted
  - invoice paid
  - OCR uploaded
  - pricing rule updated
- Present timestamps and state markers.

2.15 Add pending payments widget
- Show overdue and pending invoice counts.
- Highlight financial risk clearly.

2.16 Add supply chain activity snapshot
- Show partner sync status.
- Show upstream/downstream activity.
- Show recent changes in relationship data.

PHASE 4 — PROJECTS MODULE

2.17 Build the project list page
- Create a dense table with:
  - project name
  - client
  - total SFT
  - status
  - cost estimate
  - progress
- Add filters by:
  - status
  - client
  - date
  - project type
- Add row actions:
  - view
  - edit
  - process
  - duplicate
  - archive

2.18 Build project detail screen
- Add a master-detail layout.
- Show project metadata at top.
- Include tabs or sections for:
  - drawings / measurements
  - BOM
  - cost breakdown
  - pricing applied
  - invoices
  - activity log

2.19 Build drawings / measurements section
- Display structured measurements.
- Use annotated cards or technical table views.
- Highlight key inputs needed for fabrication.

2.20 Build BOM section
- Include:
  - profiles
  - glass
  - hardware
  - quantities
- Show consumption mapping from project to material requirements.
- Support preview mode before processing.

2.21 Build cost breakdown
- Split cost into:
  - materials
  - labor
  - overhead
  - margin
  - taxes
- Show subtotal and final estimate.
- Keep the display transparent and audit-friendly.

2.22 Build pricing applied section
- Show which pricing rule was applied.
- Show region/customer/material match.
- Explain the price logic in a visible UI way.

2.23 Build linked invoices section
- Show invoice linkage to the project.
- Include invoice status and due date.
- Allow navigation to payment module.

2.24 Add process project action
- Create a workflow modal or drawer.
- Simulate:
  - SFT usage deduction
  - inventory deduction preview
  - cost estimation
  - final confirmation
- Show before/after state.
- Make the business logic visible in the UI.

PHASE 5 — INVENTORY MODULE

2.25 Build inventory overview cards
- Profiles
- Glass
- Hardware
- Show stock quantity and alert states.

2.26 Build inventory table
- Include:
  - item name
  - category
  - quantity
  - unit
  - warehouse/location
  - status
- Use clear visual severity for:
  - in stock
  - low
  - out
- Support filters by category, location, and status.

2.27 Build stock in / stock out UI
- Add stock adjustment flow.
- Include quantity, reason, source, and location.
- Simulate add stock and remove stock actions.

2.28 Build low stock warning system
- Show alert cards and inline indicators.
- Surface urgent items first.
- Make action buttons available for reorder or stock correction.

2.29 Build multi-level visibility toggle
- Allow switching visibility modes:
  - fabricator
  - distributor
  - trader
- Change what the user sees based on the selected level.
- Keep this as a UI simulation only.

2.30 Build BOM auto-deduction preview panel
- Show what inventory will be consumed when a project is processed.
- Display item-by-item deductions.
- Show estimated remaining quantity after processing.

PHASE 6 — PRICING ENGINE MODULE

2.31 Build pricing rule management screen
- Present a list of pricing rules.
- Show:
  - region
  - customer type
  - material
  - price per SFT
  - margin
  - markup
- Allow edit / delete actions from row controls.

2.32 Build rule builder UI
- Create a structured condition builder.
- Allow conditions for:
  - region
  - material
  - customer type
- Allow output definitions:
  - price per SFT
  - margin
  - markup

2.33 Build pricing preview panel
- Show the resulting calculated price.
- Indicate which rules matched.
- Display rule priority and fallback logic visually.

2.34 Support multiple pricing strategies
- Region-based pricing
- Customer-type pricing
- Bulk pricing
- Material-specific pricing
- Add priority handling UI.

PHASE 7 — BILLING & WALLET MODULE

2.35 Build wallet balance section
- Show current balance prominently.
- Show available credits.
- Show recent usage.
- Show replenishment state.

2.36 Build credit purchase UI
- Allow mock purchase flow.
- Simulate package selection.
- Show transaction confirmation state.

2.37 Build usage deduction history
- Show:
  - SFT used
