- No reports available

2.74 Improve all error states
- Validation failure
- Sync failure
- Out of stock
- Overdue payments
- Missing OCR fields

2.75 Add UX micro-interactions
- Hover states
- Row highlights
- Drawer transitions
- Badge updates
- Confirmation feedback

2.76 Ensure consistency across modules
- Same spacing rhythm
- Same color semantics
- Same table patterns
- Same action patterns
- Same badge language

2.77 Make the system feel real
- Use realistic names, numbers, dates, and statuses.
- Avoid placeholder-looking junk.
- Keep every screen business-credible.

3) IMPLEMENTATION ORDER / PRIORITY

3.1 Build first
- App shell
- Navigation
- Design system
- Mock data
- Shared components

3.2 Build next
- Dashboard
- Projects
- Inventory
- Pricing Engine

3.3 Then build business operations
- Billing & Wallet
- Payments
- Supply Chain
- OCR Uploads

3.4 Then build reporting and scale features
- Reports
- Batch Processing
- Admin Panel
- Offline mode
- Multi-language support

3.5 Final pass
- Polish
- responsiveness
- edge states
- visual consistency
- interaction quality

4) ACCEPTANCE CRITERIA

4.1 The UI must feel enterprise-grade
- Not toy-like.
- Not overly decorative.
- Not visually noisy.
- Not empty or generic.

4.2 The app must clearly communicate
- monetization
- operations
- finance
- intelligence
- ecosystem connectivity

4.3 Every major module must have
- a main view
- detail view or drilldown
- state indicators
- mock data
- action patterns

4.4 The product must be shippable in structure
- If backend is added later, the UI should already be logically organized for integration.

5) FINAL OUTCOME

- A polished SaaS-grade Fabricator Management Platform UI.
- Clear operational depth.
- Strong financial and billing visibility.
- Serious enterprise UX.
- Mocked but believable workflows.
- Ready for backend integration later without redesigning the core structure.
